{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1lichtenstein_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280601676/1938010601/0558.xml":{"full_text":"THE EVENING STAR\nWith Sunday Marnlng Edition\nTHEODORE W. NOYES, Editor\nWASHINGTON, D. C.\nTHURSDAY ....January 8, 1938\nThe Evening Star Newspaper Company\nMain Offlce: 11th St. and Pennsylvania Ave.\nNew York Offlce: 110 East 42nd St.\nChicago Offlce: 435 North Michigan Ava.\nDelivered by Carrier\u2014City and Suburban\nRerular Edition\nEvening and Sunday. 65c per mo. or 15e per weel\nThe Evening Star_45c per mo. or 10c per week\nThe Sunday Star___ 5c per copy\nNight Final Edition\nNight Final and Sunday Star_70c per month\nNight Final S'ar _ ._ ASe per mouth\nCollection made at the end of each month or\neach week. Orders may be sen: by mail or lele\nphone National 5000.\nI\nRate by Mail\u2014Payable In Advance\nMaryland and Virginia\nDally and Sunday.\u201e1 yr.. $1000; 1 mo.. 85c\nDally only-1 yr., $0.00; 1 mo.. Sue\nBunday only-1 yr\u201e $4.00; 1 mo.. 40c\nAll Other States and Canada\nDally and Sunday.l yr.. $12.00; 1 mo., $1.00\nDally only-1 yr., $8.00; 1 mo., 75c\n\u2022unday only-1 yr., $5.00; 1 mo\u201e 60c\nMember of the Associated Presi\nThe Associated Press is exclusively entitled to\nthe use for republicauon of all news dispatches\ncredited to It or not otherwise credited m this\nPaPer a^s0 the local news published herein.\nAll rights of publication of special dispatches\nherein also are reserved.\nThe District Budget.\nAs sent to Congress yesterday, the\nDistrict budget pictures a definite con\ntinuation of the trend toward increasing\nthe local taxpayers' financial respon\nsibility in connection with maintenance\nand development of the Capital, while\ndecreasing the financial responsibility of\nthe National Government without any\nlessening of its exclusive political control.\nThe lump sum. it is true, remains at\nthe inadequate figure of $5,000,000 under\nbudget recommendations. To have pro\nposed another decrease at the expense\nof local taxpayers would be to threaten\nthem with bankruptcy. As it is, the in\ncrease in budget demands\u2014the respon\nsibility for preventing a deficit between\nrevenue and expenditures\u2014is charged to\nthe local taxpayer exclusively. And that\nmeans another boost in local taxes on\ntop of the boost applied in the current\nfiscal year.\nThe cost of street lighting, hitherto\nborne as a charge divided, though un\nevenly, between the National Govern\nment and the general taxpayer, is trans\nferred exclusively to the automobile\nowner. The cost of streets has already\nbeen placed almost entirely on the auto\nmobile owner, with consequent relief to\nthe National Government which designed\nand has embellished a costly street sys\ntem befitting the National Capital. The\nfantastic additional result of this move\nmay be further discrimination against\nthe District in the allotment of Federal\nhighway-aid funds, on the ground that\nhighway funds will not be given to local\ngovernments which practice gasoline\ntax diversion.\nThe entire cost of the expensive tunnel\ntreatment at Dupont Circle\u2014an under\ntaking peculiarly associated with the\nproblems resulting from the design of\nthe National Capital\u2014is placed on the\nautomobile taxpayer, with no participa\ntion by the National Government pri\nmarily responsible for creation of the\nproblems.\nThe budget estimates contain funds\nfor starting the first unit of the elaborate\nMunicipal Center, an undertaking many\ntimes revised at the expense of the local\ntaxpayer. But no extra participation by\nthe National Government, responsible\nfor the Municipal Center project, is pro\nvided although such participation was\ntacitly guaranteed at the time of the\napproval of the Municipal Center plan.\nLocal taxpayers by now should be\nfamiliar with the various steps, too com\nplicated and extensive to repeat here,\nby which this process of unloading the\nlion\u2019s share of expense on the local tax\npayer has been accomplished. The cur\nrent budget is merely a continuation of\nthat process. How long can it continue,\nwithout saddling the local taxpayer with\na burden far heavier than his resources\npermit him to carry? It will continue\nas long as the local taxpayer is able to\npay. He may be forced into bankruptcy\nin the process. He may be forced to\nseek residence outside the heavily taxed\nDistrict, as Increasing thousands are\ndoing now. He may be forced to other\nextremes\u2014unless he demands and fights\nfor the right of representation and equal\nparticipation in the Government which\ntaxes him. If the local taxpayer does\nnot realize that now, he will realize it\nlater on when continued misgovernment,\ntaking high tribute in taxes without\ncommensurate return in sendees, finally\ndrives the lesson home.\nRetirement of a Jurist.\nThe retirement from the Supreme\nCourt of Associate Justice Sutherland\nwill remove from the bench a jurist who\nhas rendered distinguished service to his\nadopted country. Bom in England, he\nwas brought to the United States as a\nchild by his parents and grew to man\nhood in what was then the undeveloped\nWest. Before receiving his appointment\nto the Supreme Court fifteen years ago,\nJustice Sutherland had seen service in\nthe Utah Legislature, in the House of\nRepresentatives and in the Senate.\nDuring his service on the court he\nhas advocated a strict construction of\nthe Constitution and has been a devoted\nchampion of the Bill of Rights. In pass\ning on the validity of a statute there\nwas, to his mind, no room for com\npromise with expediency. \"If the pro\nvisions of the Constitution be not upheld\nwhen they pinch as well as when they\ncomfort,\u201d he once said, \"they may as\nwell be abandoned.\u201d\nBut. although his passing from the\nJudicial scene will be a loss in a very\nreal sense, it is in keeping with the true\nspirit of democracy. Justice Sutherland\nis representative of the best elements of\npolitical philosophy that has under\ngone a pronounced change in the past\nA\ndecade. A conception of the Constitu\ntion that held fast for generations has\nbeen largely replaced by a new philoso\nphy. The question is not whether this\nnew philosophy, in an economic sense,\nis right or wrong. If the spirit of de\nmocracy is to be served, it should be\ngiven a trial unless violative of our\nfundamental law.\nIt is inevitable, however, that men will\ndiffer as to the meaning of the Con\nstitution. Justice Sutherland, as a con\nscientious man, could not and would not\naccept the interpretation of the admin\nistration now in power. He had taken\nan oath to support the Constitution as\nhe understood it, and his decisions simply\nreflected his loyalty to the duty Imposed\nby that oath.\nConsequently, his decision to retire,\ncoming of his own free will and reached\nunder no political compulsion, should not\nbe viewed by those who share his beliefs\nas another element in the disintegration\nof the American state, but rather as a\nstep in the normal functioning of a\ndemocracy.\nAt the same time, his retirement poses\na challenge to the President. It is to be\nexpected that Mr. Roosevelt will nomi\nnate as a successor to Justice Sutherland\na man who agrees with the broad out\nlines of his own philosophy. If he goes\na step further and selects a nominee\nwhose judicial character and intellectual\nintegrity can match that of Justice\nSutherland he, too. will have made a\ncommendable contribution to the case\nfor democracy.\nThe Budget.\nAgain the country is faced with a\nbillion-dollar deficit\u2014and perhaps more\u2014\nat the close of the new fiscal year, which\nbegins July 1 next and ends June 30,\n1939. The Government has been in the\n\u201cred\u2019\u2019 so long, the budget has been out\nof balance for so many years that the\ncountry has almost become callous.\nAt the close of business on June 30,\n1939, the gross public debt will have\nreached the stupendous figure of $38,528,\n200,000\u2014unless it has gone higher\u2014ac\ncording to the estimates submitted to\nCongress by the President. What is to\nbe the outcome?\nPresident Roosevelt regards as of very\ngreat importance the fact that the esti\nmated expenditures for the next fiscal\nyear are $539,000,000 below those for\nthe present fiscal year which ends June\n30. Surely this is a step in the right\ndirection, and the country will agree\nwith the President that this is a salutary\nthing.\nThe difficulty about the budget sent\nto the Capitol yesterday by the President\nis found in the fact that it may be\nchanged overnight, as admitted by the\nPresident himself. He intends to ask\nfor greater appropriations for relief if\nconditions become worse and there is\ngreater unemployment. Furthermore, it\nis expected that the President will send\nanother message, dealing with national\ndefense and the need of materially ex\npanding the Navy. So this budget must\nbe regarded as a flexible matter, with\nthe estimates of expenditures already\nexpected to exceed what the President\nhas recommended. Whether there is any\n'chance for an increase in the estimated\nrevenues is another matter.\nIf the present business recession is\nhalted, if production and employment\nmove up. the chances for more revenue\nare good. But even so, the revenues\nmay not move much beyond the point\nestimated by the President in his mes\nsage. There is the chance that more taxes\nwill be levied, and so more revenue may\nbe obtained. But this chance is remote\u2014\nparticularly in view of the already heavy\ntax burden and the fact that a con\ngressional election is just around the\ncorner.\nThe President has indicated that the\nGovernment may not be forced to new\nborrowing to take care of the increase\nin the public debt, due to the deficits\ngrowing out of the present fiscal year,\nand even of the next fiscal year. It is\nplanned to make use of the revenue ob\ntained from the taxes under the social\nsecurity law, for old age pensions and\nunemployment pensions, to purchase\nGovernment securities that must be\nissued to meet these increases. Such\nfinancing will meet with disapproval, and\nalready members of Congress have de\nclared that these funds should be segre\ngated and not used to meet the general\nexpenses of government.\nThe business recession of the past six\nmonths has been the cause, the Presi\ndent says, of the failure to achieve a\nbalanced budget In the fiscal year 1939.\nHe is probably entirely correct. The\nbusiness recession, on the other hand,\nis due in considerable part to the pur\nchase of huge supplies early in 1937 by\nmany industries and businesses, because\nof the fear that prices would be forced\nhigher. The country was then suffering\nan epidemic of sit-down strikes. De\nmands for increases in wages of labor\nwere countrywide. The prospect of in\ncreased costs of production\u2014and of in\ncreased prices\u2014was imminent.\nAdministration spokesmen have charged\nthat the recession was due to a strike\nof capital, to increases in prices by\n\u2018\u2018monopolies,\" and to other bad practices\nby a minority of business men. Now,\nhowever, the President is suggesting that\nthe way to relief is collective action on\nthe part of industries\u2014which means if\nanything a tendency toward monopoly.\nThe country is still at a loss to under\nstand what the administration wants\nor intends to do. It does know, however,\nthat the end of deficits, of Government\nexpenditures in excess of Government\nreceipts, is not yet in sight.\nDelay in Palestine.\nObviously motivated by a desire not\nto aggravate the explosive Near Eastern\nsituation, Great Britain has temporarily\nshelved the plan to partition Palestine.\nThe scheme hatched by the Peel Com\nmission last summer will not be carried\ninto effect until there has been an ex\nploration of the possibilities of reshaping\nthe project on lines more acceptable to\nall concerned. A White Paper maintains\nthat tripartite subdivision \"is the best\nand most hopeful solution of the prob\nlem,\u201d but between the lines it is trans\nparent that Prime Minister Chamberlain\nand his colleagues have waning enthu\nsiasm for the decisions reached by the\ncabinet last July.\nIngenious as was the plan to carve\nseparate areas out of Palestine, consist\ning of independent Jewish and Arab\nstates and a British mandated region\nembracing Jerusalem, Bethlehem and the\nother holy places, besides a corridor to\nthe sea, it aroused bitter criticism by\nZionists, Arab Nationalists, the House of\nCommons and the League of Nations\nCouncil. Conceived in that spirit of com\npromise, which our British cousins tra\nditionally invoke on occasions of Impasse,\nand designed to appease everybody, the\narrangement pleased nobody. So Down\ning Street will try again.\nA new \"technical commission\u201d will\nnow survey the situation on the spot.\nIt has wide authority to propose modi\nfications. Particularly will be sought va\nriations of the area that was allocated\nto a British mandate. This is clearly\nintended to pacify the Jews, whose main\nlament was that the original proposal\nwould deprive them of control of Jeru\nsalem, seat of the great Hebrew Univer\nsity and other cherished Zionist cul\ntural institutions. The long delay which\nmust ensue before a substitute plan is\nevolved may encourage Jews and Arabs\nto patch up their ancient differences,\nbut the White Paper envisions ultimate\npartition as the inevitable alternative to\na demonstrably unworkable mandate.\nPartition was described in 1937 as a\n\"surgical operation.\u201d Drastic as such\nresoft to the political knife may be and\nviolative of the pledge to create a Jewish\nNational Home \\in Palestine, as Zionists\nhold it to be, many Britons consider a\nterritorial triplex unavoidable, if vital\nimperial interests\u2014namely, the urgent\nnecessity of placating a restive Moham\nmedan element athwart the empire \u201clife\nline\u201d\u2014are to be safeguarded.\nBritain, in seeking to crack the Pales\ntinian nut, has her eye not only on\nJew and Arab, but on Benito Mussolini.\nHe is the real architect of John Bull's\nsudden decision to look again before he\nleaps in the Holy Land.\nOurs is a great country with great re\nsponsibilities before it. It still has an\nabundance of wealth which awaits wise\nemployment.\nJapan has a supreme authority, the\nMikado, who may claim seclusion among\nhis own subjects, but not in the strife\ninto which his people have ventured.\nThe friends of Carter Glass are en\nthusiastically celebrating his eightieth\nbirthday by placing before him the op\nportunity for more work.\n\u201cHit and run\u201d has already claimed\nthe first D. C. motor victim for the year\n1938. In some respects the new year\nis no different from the old.\nIt is directly asserted by the President\nthat where there is a new deal it is nec\nessary to show close attention to whose\nturn it is to ante.\nAnd as Tiny Tim remarked, \u201cGod bless\nus every one,\u201d with no afterthought in\nviting the devil to take the hindmost.\nJapan has asserted a leadership*which\ncalls on the Mikado for the assumption\nof certain direct responsibilities.\nShooting Stars.\nBY PHILANDER JOHNSON.\nThe Mask and the Play.\nIn bygone days a gentle dame\nWhen to the theater she came,\nHer blushes to conceal, would ask\nProtection from a dainty mask.\nA lady now sits in the throng\nAnd hears a rather shocking song,\nWhose phrases she must not repeat;\nYet her composure is complete.\nHer lipstick, rouge and powder puff\nShe wields; not much, ljut Just enough.\nNo doubt her blushes often glow.\nIt matters\u2019not. They do not show.\nSabotage.\n\u201cAre you In control of the political\nmachine?\u201d\n\"For the present,\u201d answered Senator\nSorghum. \"But the difficulty about a\npolitical machine is that you never know\nwhen somebody is going to throw a\nmonkey wrench.\u201d\nJud Tunkins says he hopes some means\nwill be found of guaranteeing peace in\na small way by starting a league of\nneighbors.\nErratic Art.\nArtistic demonstration\nBrings mingled fear and hope.\nPart seems like \"inspiration\u201d\nAnd part seems like plain \"dope.\u201d\n\"One of lofty mind,\u201d said Hi Ho, the\nsage of Chinatown, \u201cmay fall into error\nby assuming that his ideas are shared\nby those who have not even tried to\nunderstand them.\u201d\nJulipleas Mint.\n\"Circumstantial evidence may be mis\nleading.\u201d\n\"Of course,\u201d answered Uncle Bill\nBottletop. \u201cThe more you let a mint\npatch alone the bigger it grows.\u201d\nLawbreaker.\nThe citizen may do his best\nAnd strive for freedom from arrest.\nYet, he will be accused of crime.\nSome day he will park overtime.\n\"If you takes yohself too serious,\u201d\nsaid Uncle Eben, \u201cyou is g\u2019ineter be as\nlonesome as de man dat turned his back\non de percession an* marched de other\nway.\nt 1\nIncredible Proposition to\nMake Lawbreaking Lawful\nTo th* Editor of The 8t\u00bbr:\nIt seems incredible, this latest sugges\ntion for solving the traffic problem, and\nstill more Incredible that it should come\nfrom the director of traffic and the\nsuperintendent of police.\nBriefly, the suggestion is to eliminate\nthe lawbreakers of the traffic world by\nmaking their lawbreaking lawful. Of\ncourse, the plan is not presented in as\nsimple words as these. We are to have\nIncreased speed, as a ctfre for the present\nvicious and inexcusable traffic conditions\nwhich are almost solely the direct result\nof speed. This will mean less effort\nin the way of law enforcement, and will\nat least relieve the hapless pedestrian\nof the effort he has been making for\nsome time to belive that those in au\nthority were really concerned about his\nsafety.\nAny thinking and considerate driver,\nwith any amount of experience to his\ncredit, can testify to the narrow escapes\nfrom injury to himself and others, and\nthe number of accidents he has avoided,\nby maintaining a reasonable and con\ntiollable speed. In the face of traffic\nconditions in this city, where the toll\nis chiefly old people and young children,\nany reasoning person must admit that\nspeed and speed alone is the killing fac\ntor in the great majority of the fatal\nor nearly fatal accidents. Our heartless\nregulations, and our heartless drivers,\nmany of whom are not of an age to\nhave any judgment or to think of any\none but themselves, take no account now\nof the^ many who are forced to use our\nstreets and who are unfortunately not\nin a condition to \"step on it\u2019\u2019 to get\nout of the path of conscienceless motor\nists whose very manner of handling their\ncars proves them utterly unfit to have\na license.\nme plan is, according to reports, to\nraise the speed from 22 and 30 to 25\nand 35 miles an hour in the various\nzones. The sequel is most interesting.\nAll who violate this new speed limit\nare to be arrested. It seems that at\npresent drivers are going at 25 and 30\nmiles in 22-mile zones and at 35 and\nover in 30-mile zones, so the idea is to\nraise the limit, on the supposition that\nthe lawless drivers will immediately\nthereafter conform to the new law. And\nwhy should they? What is to hinder\ntheir raising their speed again above\nthe new limit? And how are they to be\narrested, if at the present time the police\nare entirely unable to catch them, only\na tiny proportion of the actual violators\nbeing apprehended as things are now?\nUnder the new limits the drinking driver\nwill also be able to get by easier, until\nhe is stopped by a casualty or fatality.\nThe idea always seems to be, if it is\ndifficult to enforce any law, just repeal\nthe law, then the problem of enforce\nment is easy. Why not apply the same\nline of reasoning to the law against mur\nder, since murderers are even now being\nexcused on the slightest pretext.\nAs has been said many times before\nthe whole problem can be worked out\nwithout reducing it to the absurdity of\nincreased speed, by a process of elimina\ntion. Take the killer off the streets,\nat least for a sufficiently long period\nto let him throuoghlv digest his re\nsponsibility, and the sad consequences of\nhis selfishness. Don't let him run down\nan aged couple one day and ride around\nin his car the next day, protected by\nthe bail of some sympathetic friend.\nWhen a robber is caught red-handed with\na gun, he is not released to do his own\nfree will before his dead are even buried,\nnor allowed to keep the weapon with\nwhich he killed his victim.\nIt is self-evident and capable of proof\nthat it is fast driving, and not slow driv\ning, that creates traffic hazards. Any\nmere child can figure this out. And it is\nalso evident that the constant sugges\ntions in favor of more speed appearing\nevery now- and then In the dailv papers\n8re 8 very important factor In the en\ncouragement of lawbreakers.\nVERA E. ADAMS.\nMotorist-Pedestrian Finds\nOnly Jaywalking Is Safe\nTo the Editor of The Star:\nWhile walking to work this morning\nI had two narrow escapes from wild mo\ntorists making right-hand turns. When\nI think of similar incidents in the past,\nI conclude that I possess either a\ncharmed life or an uncanny ability to\nrevert to side-stepping tactics learned on\na school gridiron.\nThis current talk about pedestrian\ncontrol and the jaywalking menace in\ncenses me no little, because I am both a\nmotorist and a pedestrian and I know\nwhat both are up against, and it is my\nfirm conviction that any corrective and\nrestrictive measures should be aimed not\nat the pedestrian but squarely at the\nmotorist. I am perfectly willing to cross\nan intersection with the green signal if\nI can do so with safety, but how can this\nbe possible when vehicular traffic uses\nthe same signal to make right and left\nturns, oftentimes marooning the pedes\ntrian in the middle of the street as the\nlights change? This has occurred to me\nso many times until I find many inter\nsections can be crossed more expedi\ntiously and with greater safety on the\nred light. An example is Pennsylvania\navenue at Thirteenth street N.W. Given\nthe green signal, one does not dare ven\nture out on the street unless he wants\nto take issue with the steady stream of\ncars rounding the corner\u2014the outcome\nof which is easily predictable. On the\nred light, however, one can usually cross\nwithout difficulty. If this makes one a\njaywalker, it is all right with me. because\nI would rather be a live jaywalker and\ncross on the red than a dead pedestrian\nwho waited for the green.\nH. C. WILLIAMS.\nHow Many Americans\nAre Now Unemployed?\nTa the Editor of The 8t*r:\nThere is one thing now being printed\nthat gives me high blood pressure and\nthat is unemployment data. That state\nment that between 7.822,912 and 10,870,\n000 Americans were out of work in No\nvember. How, in the world, do we know\nhow many Americans were out of work\nat that time? There was no distinction\nbetween a citizen and the unnaturalized\non the cards sent out. Surely the un\nnaturalized cannot be called Americans.\n1 do not doubt that a large number of\naliens are listed in the millions out of\nwork. Well do I remember when un\nemployment was at its peak and how it\nwas then pointed out that several million\nforeigners were in the idle class. The\nAmerican citizen was the sufferer at that\ntime. The true American was too proud\nto ask for relief until absolutely neces\nsary. What about the unnaturalized,\ndid they seek relief at once and get it?\nJust ask the fellow who knows. I wish\nsome one big enough would come across\nand insist on legislation to protect Amer\nican citizens from the influx of cheap\nforeign labor.\nMRS. PRANK E. HICKMAN.\nJapanese Marksmanship.\nProm the Worcester Gazette.\nThe Japanese general staff is issuing\norders for increased marksmanship\ntraining, the hope being, apparently,\nthat eventually Japanese gunners will\nbe as efficient bombing the enemy as\nthey an now at hitting neutrals.\nt\nTHIS AND THAT\nBY CHARLES E. TRACEWELL.\nIt has been a good winter for grass.\nEspecially for fresh new blades which\nsprang up last fall, following the sowing\nof seed.\nHarsh weather in December would\nhave killed much of this new crop, but\nto date the elements have been kindly,\nfostering it well.\nHence many lawns look in better con\ndition in the new year than they had\npreviously for many winters.\nThis is always good news to the garden\nlover, who must find little to do in the\nyard at this time of year.\nHe is all the more likely, therefore,\nto concentrate on the lawn, perennial\nfavorite of the famous fireside gardener.\n\nThe term denotes the dreaming which\nis done at this time of year.\nThinking, rather than dreaming, per\nhaps.\nAnything worth doing is worth think\ning about, even dreaming about.\nDuring the growing season of spring\nand summer there Is so much to be done\noutdoors that little time is left for any\nthing else.\nSo it is fortunate winter comes.\nIt gives even the most enthusiastic\ngardener, the mild nuisance kind, an\nopportunity to straighten things out.\n\nIt is all too true that many persons\nget themselves into mental snarls be\ncause they won\u2019t do this.\nThey haven't time, they say.\nThey won\u2019t take the time to stop, look\nand listen\u2014to think, in other words\u2014\nbecause they haven't the time.\nIt all works out to a vicious circle.\n\u201cLike dumb, driven cattle,\u201d Indeed, we\nare, if we honestly haven't the time to\nthink a bit, or. what is even worse, if we\nwill not give ourselves the time.\nthe weather has been what Is commonly\ncalled open.\nThis has meant that the fresh new\nblades of all fall-sown grass have had\nevery opportunity to grow and thrive.\nReal growth means root growth.\nYet the days have been so mild, com\nparatively speaking, that the grass blades\nhave received plenty of warmth and\nsunshine, and enough rain to carry them\nalong.\nAll this contributes to root growth.\nAnother helpful factor is negative\u2014tree\nroots are dormant, and therefore do not\ntake away food from the grass.\n\nOften the failure of autumn planted\ngrass seed has hinged on a too early cold\nspell, which in turn usually means an\nintensely dry spell.\nFresh grass cannot stand these inimi\ncal factors, but probably no real harm\nwould be done if the root growth were\nestablished.\nWhen cold and ice come in early De\ncember, even seed sown in late August\nhas not time to get going well.\nWhen practically the whole end of the\nyear is added to the growing season,\nthe roots have had time to get well estab\nlished.\nThe hope Is that from now on no\namount of bad weather can kill the roots.\n\nIfr Is upon this new grass that an\naverage lawn must depend for future\nfreshening.\nEven lawns Into which no seed is\npoured by the owner get a great deal\nof fresh grass just the same. Nature,\nin her wisdom, takes care of that. The\nhome gardener, over the centuries, is a\ncomparatively new creature. Nature does\nnot know' whether she can depend upon\nhim or not. So she does not trust him\ntoo far. She continues right along with\nher old tested ways. That is why some\namateurs in the past have been able to\nsneer at the idea of fall-sown seed.\nNature was working for them, though\nthey gave her no credit.\nw w w- m\nIt really is a good thing for the garden\ning hobby\u2014it may be called that, with\nno disrespect\u2014that winter Intervenes.\nThis would seem a heavenly dispensa\ntion, then, and it is; it means that\nwhether the enthusiast likes it or not.\nhe must slow down a bit, let his yard\nalone, must think and dream, and so\nplan.\nPlanning, fortunately, with any good\nfortune at all, may be carried out very\nnicely in a small garden.\nWhether it can be worked out on any\nlarger scale is a matter for theorists and\npoliticians to quarrel over.\nThe yard is no place for fussing. It\nis a place for making dreams come true.\n\nFirst, there must be some dream, some\nidea, to be carried out later.\nFireside gardening, as it is called, mav\nmean the planning of an entirely new\ngarden.\nIt may mean making over an old one,\nwhen the time comes.\nIt may mean nothing more drastic\nthan digging up old outworn shrubs\nand evergreens and putting in respec\ntable new specimens.\nIt may mean renovating a lawn.\n\nIt has been a very helpful thing that\nIce and snow and cold, from now on,\nought to leave most of the new grass\nin good root shape for early spring\ngrowth.\nThat is the theory of fall planting,\nand, with any fortune at all, that is the\nway it works out.\nMuch depends upon whether harsh\nwinds have been too drying.\nLittle if any aid can be given a lawn\nwith the garden hose in wunter. Who,\nindeed, ever heard of any one watering\nthe grass in winter?\nIt just isn't done.\nThe time may come when it is O. K.\nin a gardening sense, but so far in the\ncenturies the gardener out with his hose\nin January would be regarded as balmy\nas the Englishman who first introduced\nthe umbrella in London.\nThere is little question that water\nshould be given evergreens when they\nget dry, seasons notwithstanding.\nNo doubt if brave persons watered\ntheir thuyas and hemlocks and spruces\nduring the winter, the passerby would\nnot see so many brown and withered\nspecimens in spring and summer.\nSTARS, MEN AND ATOMS\nNotebook of Science Progress in Field,\nLaboratory and Study.\nBY THOMAS R. HENRY.\nIn prohibition days some of the vile 1\nliquor sold by bootleggers used to be\nreferred to as \"liquid Are.\u201d\nTo John Paul Jones this would have\nbeen a perfectly plausible description.\nWhen the tempestuous sailor gulped a\nswig of rum aboard the Bon Homme\nRichard he thought he was swallowing\nfire enclosed in little capsules. For the\nnaval hero of the Revolution was largely\na self-educated man and he had read\ncarefully a six-volume book: \"Nature\nRevealed,\u201d being discourses on such par\nticulars of natural history as were\nthought proper to excite the curiosity\nand form the minds of youth.\nThis work has recently turned up in\nthe library of St. John's College at An\nnapolis. Each volume carries the signa\nture: \"John Paul Jones.\u201d The books\nshow signs of having been read over and\nover again, especially the chapters deal\ning with astronomy and navigation.\nPoring over the volumes one hits\non the long discarded phlogiston theory\nof fire. It was held by the best chem\nists of John Paul Jones\u2019 day and afforded\na perfect explanation of how something\ncold, like wine, could yet produce heat\nin the body. To quote from the old\nchemistry:\n\"What seems certain concerning fire:\n\"Fire does not consist, as modern\nphilosophers commonly pretend, of a\nswift motion of all kinds of matter, but\nis a real body. It is an element very\ndifferent from all other elements. It is\na fluid. It is a fluid prodigiously elastic\nand whose spring may be infinitely aug\nmented. It is ft body which can neither\nbe produced nor destroyed by any natural\ncause.\n\u201cAll such bodies as may be equally\nagitated ought to be equally combustible\nwere a great motion and fire but one and\nthe same thing. We nevertheless ex\nperience the contrary. The same agita\ntion of the millstone which grinds corn\nwithout producing the last sparkle af\nfords an immense quantity of them, and\nwill even set the mill on flre, when the\nupper stone rubbing immediately upon\nthe other, the inflexible surfaces crush\nthe air intercepted between them, and\nhaving no retreat it accelerates the flre\nresiding in the air.\n\u201cFire is so truly a real body that it\ndilates all the bodies it enters into. An\niron bar, made red hot, becomes a little\nlonger and broader than before. The\niron gauge or measure, which serves as\na standard in some court and in public\nmarkets, does not always agree with it\nself. It lengthens half a line or even\nmore in summer time and shortens in\nextremest cold. The pendulums of\nclocks lengthen a small matter toward\nthe equator.\n\"Fire is a fluid and its tendency to\nward spreading everywhere is an effect\nof its fluidity. It is because flre is a very\npenetrating fluid that it always en\ndeavors to be everywhere on a level, or\nin a scale of equilibrium. The flre, by\ninsinuating itself into bodies, does then\nendeavor to spread therein, in an equal\nquantity on all sides, and thereby mani\nfests it fluidity to us. This fluidity of\nflre affords an easy means to account\nhow a liquor so full of flre as wine is\nmay nevertheless be cooled to such a\ndegree as to appear as cold as ice. The\nsecret flre, which with some other prin\nciples makes up the quantity and strength\nof the liquor is as it were shut up and\nenclosed in cases which are able to\nbridle it in spite of its activity. This\nessential flre is not in the interstices of\nthe wine but in the little masses that\ncompose it. And when the liquor seems\ncool notwithstanding that internal flre,\nit is because the air of the cellar, con\ntaining less flre than the outward air,\nsheds a less quantity of it through the\npores of the glass Into the interstices of\nthe liquor. If the same wine afterward\ngrows hot in the air it Is because the\nfire in the air is a fluid which has a ten\ndency to enter whatever is offered to it.\n\"No doubt you would be glad to con\nceive how the dissolution of salt can\nrender a liquid colder. The most satis\nfactory account I can give you upon that\nhead, is, that water, having no other\naction and fluidity but what it receives\nfrom the fire spreading in its pores so\nsoon as that action shall begin to com\nmunicate itself to the salt, and reduce\nthem also into a liquor, the water neces\nsarily loses by their division. It loses the\nmore, because it is the property of salt\nto imprison fire closely, and as it were,\nto chain it up. And the ground of this\nis. that the little laminae of salt are\nmore impenetrable by fire than any other\nelement. The loss which water suffers\nof that fire which is dispersed and cap\ntivated between the laminae of salt, is\nso great that It often times is followed\nby a perfect congelation. Nay. a canful\nof salt and snow- mixed together, and\napplied on the outside of a bottle, is suf\nficient, to rob the water it contains of all\nits fire, and to imprison it so far as to\nmake the water of the bottle freeze, even\nin the middle of the summer.\"\nTwo ancient North American cultures\nare linked in pottery fragments found\nby Dr. Waldo R. Wedel. Smithsonian\nInstitution archeologist, at a site near\nKansas City this summer.\nFirst is that of the mound builders,\nthe prehistoric people who constructed\nthe great mounds in Ohio and Illinois.\nNobody knows who they were or where\nthey came from. There was no tradi\ntion concerning them among the In\ndians inhabiting the area when the first\nwhite explorers arrived.\nDuring the last few years pottery' of\na design characteristic of these mound\nbuilders has been found in Louisiana.\nThis design is diagnostic. No other an\ncient people had anything closely re\nsembling it. The Southern mound\nbuilders were apparently at a lower cul\ntural level than those of the Midwest.\nThey may have migrated northward\nalong the Mississippi, advancing in cul\nture as they went on. It is possible,\nhowever, that the Northern mound\nbuilders went South and deteriorated\nalong the way. The sites cannot be\ndated geologically.\nSecond is the culture of the sedentary,\nagricultural people who once inhabited\nNebraska and Kansas long before the\ncoming of the nomadic, hunting tribes\nencountered by the white men. They\nwere farmers, believed to have been\ndriven from their lands by successive\ndroughts similar to those of the last few\nyears. Everywhere through the region\ntheir remains are found at the lowest\narcheological level, indicating that they\nwere the earliest settled inhabitants of\nthe area.\nTheir pottery also is characteristic,\nchiefly because of their use of a paddle\nwrapped with cord in shaping it. This\npractice apparently was general for the\nwhole region.\nAt the Kansas City site Dr. Wedel\nfound mixed together pottery frag\nments of both designs and some in which\ncombinations of both occur on the same\npieces. The implication is clear that\nthere was a mound builder\u2014Western\nfarmer liaison.\nThere is no means of telling. Mr. Wedel\nsaid, which came first or from what di\nrection the meeting took place. There\nis also no indication of the relationship\nbetween the two peoples and it may\nhave been either friendly or hostile.\nMore evidence will be needed for a valid\ninterpretation, but the find promises to\nbe of considerable importance in\nstraightening the tangle of North Amer\nica's prehistoric past 1\nA\nANSWERS TO\nQUESTIONS\nBY FREDERIC J. HASKIN.\nA reader can get the answer to any\nQuestion of fact by writing The Evening\nStar Information Bureau, Frederic J.\nHaskin, director, Washington, D. C.\nPlease inclose stamp for reply.\nQ. Do drunken pedestrians figure In\nautomobile accidents?\u2014G. M.\nA. A survey by the Massachusetts\nSafety Council shows that they are al\nmost as great a menace as drunken driv\ners. In 412 night highway accidents in\nthat State in 1936 almost a third more\nintoxicated pedestrians were victims than\nintoxicated drivers.\nQ. What is the fastest sport?\u2014H. C. S.\nA. Ice hockey is so considered.\nQ. What is the old Fine Arts Build\ning of the 1893 Chicago Fair now used\nfor?\u2014F. M.\nA. It is now the Museum of Science\nand Industry. The building has been\nentirely restored and Julius Rosenwald\nhas provided the funds for the museum.\nQ. What day of the week was July 4,\n1776?\u2014M. W.\nA. It fell on a Thursday.\nQ. How high should a barbed-wire\nfence be for confining sheep, goats and\ncows?\u2014A. A. P.\nA. The Bureau of Agricultural Engi\nneering says that barbed wire is not very\nsuitable for a sheep fence, since it tears\nthe wool. If used, the fence may be\nthree feet high, with the wires about six\ninches apart. For goats, the fence should\nbe five feet high, made of six or seven\nwires. A fence four and one-half feet\nhigh with five wires may be used for\ncows.\nQ. May a person publish a letter that\nhe has received without the consent of\nthe writer?\u2014W. K.\nA. This Is a legal question. The fol\nlowing is an excerpt from Corpus Juris,\nvolume 13: \u201cThe writer of a letter has\na right of property in the letter, superior\nto that of the person to whom the letter\nis sent, which entitles the writer to a\nremedy against any unauthorized publi\ncation, either by the person to whom it\nwas sent or by a stranger. As in the\ncase of art works, the common law lit\nerary property may be in the sender,\nwhile the title to the physical substance\nof the letter may be in the recipient.\nThe recipient has the property right in\nthe paper on which the letter is written;\nhe may keep it or destroy it, and he can\nrecover possession of it when lost, even\nfrom the writer; but he has no right to\npublish it without the consent of the\nwriter. It has been said that the recip\nient of a letter may publish it against\nthe will of the WTiter where it is neces\nsary to protect his rights or to defend\nhis character against the writer; but this\ndoctrine has been severely criticized and\nit is doubtful if it would now be fol\nlowed.\"\nQ. Where Is the original manuscript\nof Barne s \u201cPeter and Wendy\"?\u2014W. H.\nA. It was recently purchased at auc\ntion in London by Gabriel Wells of New\nYork.\nQ. Is Bessie Smith, the Negro blues\nsinger, living?\u2014W. J*\nA. She died last September as the re\nsult of an automobile accident. The\nsinger was 41 years old.\nQ. Is the work-study plan at Antioch\nCollege successful to the extent of get\nting jobs for students?\u2014H. W.\nA. Less than 2 per cent of the grad\nuates of Antioch College in the last 15\nyears are unemployed.\nQ. What States put their government\nemployes under civil service in 1937?\u2014\nG R.\nA. As a result of 1937 legislation, Mich\nigan. Connecticut. Arkansas, Maine and\nTennessee adopted the system.\nQ. How did Sir Walter Scott hear of\nthe American Jewess. Rebecca Gratz,\nwho is believed to have inspired the\nRebecca in \"Ivanhoe\"?\u2014L. T.\nA. She was a friend of the Matilda\nHoffman to whom Washington Irving\nwas engaged. She nursed Miss Hoffman,\nwho died of tuberculosis. Irving related\nthe tale of her devotion to Scott.\nQ. What is the origin of the expres\nsion, \u201cThe real McCoy\"?\u2014J. A. D.\nA. There are several tales as to its\norigin. Gov. A1 Smith of New York\ngives the following: \u201cEvery small town\nin the United States has what we call\nan oracle, who knows a little bit of\neverything. The oracle of the Bowery\nmany years ago was a man by the name\nof McCoy, so that when any matter\ncame up 'It's the real McCoy\u2019 came Into\nbeing and usually in this manner: \u2019Well,\nI will give you the low down on that!\nI will give you the inside story, the real\nMcCoy.'\nQ. When was the mace first used in\nthe House of Representatives?\u2014H. E. A.\nA. The first mace of the House of\nRepresentatives was adopted April 4.\n1789. It was about three feet lone and\nconsisted of 13 ebony rods, representing\nthe 13 original colonies, bound together\nwith transverse bands of stiver in imi\ntation of the thongs that bound the\nfasces of ancient Rome. The shaft was\nsurmounted by a globe of solid silver\nabout five inches in diameter, upon which\nrested a massive eagle, richly carved, of\nsolid silver; although the eagle's wings\nwere outspread, he grasped the globe\nfirmly with his claws. This mace was\ndestroyed bv the British when they\nburned the Capitol in 1814. For 28 years\nthereafter a mace of painted pine tvood\nwas used, until the congressional session\nof 1841-42. when the present mace was\nprocured, w\u2019hlch is a replica of the one\ndestroyed by the British.\nQ. Is there a mansion on the King\nRanch in Texas?\u2014H. K.\nA. Santa Gertrudis. the $250,000 Moor\nish style mansion on the property, haa\n18 bedrooms, each with a connecting\nbath, and a fireplace in every room.\nA Rhyme at Twilight\nBy\nGertrude Brooke Hamilton.\nA Light Sketch\nLast night Jack Frost came again,\nEtching on my window pane\nTendrils of a fragile vine,\nDaisy-stars and leaves of pine;\nAll in glittering white he sketched them,\nAs if from the woods he'd fetched them.\nFor the woods were clad In white;\nSnow had fallen all the night,\nRimmed the bare boughs of the trees\nWith an alabaster frieze;\nLightly snow had fallen on them;\nLightly Jack Frost breathed upon them.\nBut Aurora proclaimed morn,\nAnd the winter day was born.\nUp arose the merry sun,\nIdlv viewed the etching done,\nKnew Jack Frost had lightly traced it,\nLaughed; and with light rays erased It.\nM A","height":"31340","width":"22436"}}
